<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  OWASP Dependency Check Suppression File

  Each suppression must be reviewed and approved before adding.
  Document why the CVE is not applicable to this project.
-->
<suppressions xmlns="https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/dependency-suppression.1.3.xsd">

  <!--
    CVE-2021-42574 & CVE-2021-42694: Trojan Source (CVSS 8.3)

    These CVEs describe attacks where malicious Unicode bidirectional control
    characters or homoglyphs hide malicious code from human reviewers while
    compilers/interpreters execute it.

    Why NOT applicable to mermaid-mcp:

    1. STRICT SECURITY MODE: We explicitly configure Mermaid with
       securityLevel: "strict" which encodes all HTML tags in text and
       completely disables click handlers - no JavaScript execution path exists.

    2. DOMPURIFY SANITIZATION: Mermaid uses DOMPurify to sanitize all output,
       stripping dangerous elements (script, iframe, object, embed) and
       event handler attributes (onclick, onerror, onload, etc.).

    3. OUTPUT IS STATIC SVG: This tool renders diagrams to static SVG images.
       Even if LLM-generated input contains Unicode tricks, the sanitized
       output cannot execute code.

    4. ATTACK VECTOR MISMATCH: Trojan Source requires a human code review
       deception -> compilation/execution flow. A diagram renderer has no
       such flow - input is sanitized, output is an image.

    Approved: 2025-12-31
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes><![CDATA[
      Trojan Source: Bidirectional text attack. Not applicable - this tool
      renders diagrams to SVG with securityLevel:strict, no code execution.
    ]]></notes>
    <cve>CVE-2021-42574</cve>
  </suppress>

  <suppress>
    <notes><![CDATA[
      Trojan Source: Homoglyph attack. Not applicable - same rationale as
      CVE-2021-42574. Output is static SVG, not executable code.
    ]]></notes>
    <cve>CVE-2021-42694</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    CVE-2026-23864: OWASP DC CPE-matching false positive against react

    OWASP Dependency Check matches the npm `react` package against the CPE
    `cpe:2.3:a:facebook:react`, which is shared with unrelated products and
    historically produces false positives. The official npm advisory database
    (npm audit) and GitHub Security Advisories list NO CVE affecting
    `react` >= 0.14.0 as of 2026-05-26 — only ancient pre-0.14 XSS issues.

    Why NOT applicable to mermaid-mcp:

    1. TRANSITIVE DEV-ONLY DEPENDENCY: react is pulled in via
       @mermaid-js/mermaid-cli -> @mermaid-js/mermaid-zenuml -> @zenuml/core
       solely so the ZenUML diagram type can render inside the headless
       browser. We never ship React to end users.

    2. OUTPUT IS STATIC SVG: The server runs Mermaid (incl. ZenUML) in a
       sandboxed puppeteer page, serializes the rendered SVG, and returns
       the SVG string. No React runtime is exposed to clients.

    3. NO LIVE ADVISORY: `npm audit` returns 0 vulnerabilities for the full
       tree on this lockfile. The CVE only fires through OWASP DC's CPE
       matcher, which is the classic source of react FPs.

    Approved: 2026-05-26
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes><![CDATA[
      False positive from OWASP DC CPE matcher against npm `react`.
      No matching advisory in npm/GHSA databases for react >= 0.14.0.
      React is transitive via @mermaid-js/mermaid-cli; output is static SVG.
    ]]></notes>
    <packageUrl regex="true">^pkg:npm/react@.*$</packageUrl>
    <cve>CVE-2026-23864</cve>
  </suppress>

</suppressions>
